    MSC Nastran Demonstration Problems Introduction679 Main Index Introduction This example demonstrates the high-performance nonlinear solver (NLPERF) in MSC Nastran. This model features glued and frictional contact, bolt preloading, and large displacement effects. The performance is compared to the classic SOL 400 solver (CNLS). The results are compared noting differences seen in contact force output and additional items such as default contact related outputs included in the f06, MUMPS solver messaging in the f04, iteration messages in the itr file, and use of the convergence GUI monitor. The focus of this problem is the activation and outputs from the NLPERF based analysis, not the model setup. Prior chapters cover assembly modeling using contact in SOL 400 and bolt preload analyses in detail. Solution Requirements The leaf spring is modeled with node-to-segment contact to form the assembly and is loaded following a typical bolt preloading, locking, then load application approach. This solution uses a single SOL 400 SUBCASE with three STEPS. In the first step, the BOLT1 control grids are free with FORCEs applied to generate a preload. In the second step, the Boundary conditions Partially fixed at eyes of the main Leaf (Y, Z, RX, RY) Select grids along length in XY plane fixed in Z to promote symmetric solution. Step 1: •Bolt control nodes free. •Middle of lower central clamp plate fixed. Step 2: •Bolt control nodes fixed in preloaded state. •Middle of lower central clamp plate fixed. Step 3: •Bolt control nodes fixed in preloaded state. •Middle of lower central clamp plate partially fixed (X, Z, RX, RY, RZ). Applied loads Step 1: Bolt preload applied to bolt control grids. Step 2: Bolt preload locked (control grids fixed and load removed). Step 3: Enforce Motion of +25. mm in Y applied to lower central clamp plate. Element type Advanced Nonlinear HEXA Elements Results Additional Debug Messaging (f04, f06) Deformed shape Contact Forces Iteration File (.itr)

In the third and final step, an upward enforced displacement (SPCD) of 25 mm is applied to deform the leaf spring. FEM Modelin g The high-performance nonlinear solver in SOL 400 (NLPERF) is activated for this model with the NLSSEL (nonlinear solver selection) option on the NLMOPTS (nonlinear multiple options) bulk data entry. In this model, NLSSEL is specified in conjunction with ASSM=ASSUMED (assumed strain formulation for the HEXA elements) and SPROPMAP=2 (activate advanced element formulation). If this is not satisfied, the Newton- Raphson iteration is repeated. If the tolerance is specified as 0 or negative on the BCPARA card, this check will be skipped. Performance Comparison between CNLS and NLPERF The leaf spring model has 183960 CHEXA elements and 239333 GRIDs providing a 0.72 M DOF model. For the sake of performance comparison between CNLS and NLPERF , this model is relatively small and can be solved on a personal workstation. Performance comparisons for larger models are discussed in the MSC Nastran 2024.1 Release Guide. The performance comparison between CNLS and NLPERF is shown in Figure 58-1 and Figure 58-2. Here, when comparing CNLS and NLPERF for runs from serial to SMP=32, we see the expected behavior that the CNLS scales well only to about 8 cores while NLPERF continues to scale up to the 32 cores tested. After 8 cores, the wall time from CNLS sees no further decrease and can increase due to increased overhead computation. In contrast, the NLPERF wall time continues to decrease. In the serial runs, NLPERF provides a 30% speedup, while comparing the best CNLS wall times (3200 s for SMP=8 and 3188 s for SMP=16) to the best observed NLPERF wall time (926 s), NLPERF offers a 3.4x speedup.

    684 Chapter 58: Leaf Spring Analysis using NLPERF Result s Main Index SINGULARITY RATIO : 8.393181E-04 END OF MATRIX SOLUTION
    WALL TIME : 7.100000E+01 CONVERGENCE SUMMARY OF ITERATION: 4 MAXIMUM RESIDUAL FORCE AT NODE 458495 DEGREE OF FREEDOM 1 IS EQUAL TO 1.299498E-05 MAXIMUM REACTION FORCE AT NODE 279923 DEGREE OF FREEDOM 2 IS EQUAL TO 7.650803E+02 FORCE RESIDUAL CONVERGENCE RATIO 1.698512E-08 MAXIMUM DISPLACEMENT CHANGE AT THE NODE 279923 DEGREE OF FREEDOM 1 IS EQUAL TO 2.489217E-06 MAXIMUM DISPLACEMENT INCREMENT AT NODE 458497 DEGREE OF FREEDOM 1 IS EQUAL TO 3.270392E-02 DISPLACEMENT CONVERGENCE RATIO 7.611370E-05 This output provides, at a glance, the singularity ratio and the critical grids participating in both the residual-based convergence criteria and the displacement-based convergence criteria. The singularity ratio (= 1/ matrix condition number), in particular, is a good measure of stability of the model. A poorly constrained model with unstable contact can have a low singularity ratio (< 1E-8). For every factor of 10 drop in singularity ratio, the accuracy of the numerical analysis drops by a factor of 10. So, it is important to have a good singularity ratio in general (>1E-6) through a combination of provided user constraints and contact constraints. If a matrix encounters non- positive definiteness, then the MUMPS solver in NLPERF will automatically invoke the non-positive definite solver and repeat the solution. Such a solution, however, reflects the basic instability of the model and should be treated with caution. Use of AUTOSPC or other direct modeling methods such as manual spring elements with small stiffness could be used to improve the matrix conditioning. In the present iteration, the graduated leaves are well-constrained through the bolts and the singularity ratio is of the order of 8.39E-4. The convergence history via the itr file has been loaded in the convergence monitoring tool in Figure 58-3. While this shows a static view, the primary use for the convergence monitoring tool is during the analysis. Both the printed output (left side) and the graphical output (right side) update automatically as the NLPERF job prints to the itr file. The top graph shows the overall incremental view of the convergence history, while the bottom graph shows the granular, cycle-based view of the convergence history. Figure 58-4 shows a section of the convergence history zoomed in to see the details of the convergence criteria (shown as horizontal dashed lines) being met. This zoom is achieved using the middle mouse wheel while hovering over the vertical axes of the graphs.

    Main Index Chapter 59: Easy-to-use Bolt Model with Large Rotation Support 59Easy-to-use Bolt Model with Large Rotation Support Summary 690 Introduction 690 FEM Modeling 691 Results 693 Input File(s) 695

    690 Chapter 59: Easy-to-use Bolt Model with Large Rotation Support Summary Main Index Summary Introduction Bolt modeling is important in the analysis of structural assemblies where parts need to be joined together using bolts or rivets. Bolt capability simulates the effect of bolt pre-tension and shortening by modifying the elements on one side of a cross-section in the bolt. The functionality also provides a general way to model pre-stressed structural components under specified loads or prescribed displacements. This example demonstrates an easy-to-use pre-tension bolt modeling capability, BOLT1, which supports SOL 400 nonlinear analysis with advanced nonlinear elements and large rotation. The BOLT1 functionality allows modeling the effect of bolt pre-tension without the need for duplicating grid points or splitting the bolt finite element mesh into top and bottom parts around the bolt cross-section. The bolt is conveniently modeled as a contiguous component and finite element mesh. The connection of the bolt cross-section with the control grid point, where the loads are applied, is taken care of by internal modifications to the cross-section elements. This greatly simplifies the bolt modeling process especially if the model has a large number of bolts. In addition, the bolt’s axial direction is continuously updated to accurately track bolt rotation. This allows the BOLT1 feature to support nonlinear analysis with large rotation. FEM Modeling Using the BOLT1 entry, the user has two options to input the data required for bolt modeling: the cross-section method and the simple method. By using the cross-section method, the user has more control in defining the bolt axial direction and cross-section selection. The user enters the vector defining the bolt axis, enters the list of grid points forming the bolt cross-section as well as the list of elements sharing cross-section grid points and lying on the opposite side of the normal vector. These are the elements that will be internally connected to the bolt control grid point. Using the simple method of BOLT1 entry, modeling of bolts is further simplified by not requiring the user to enter the bolt axial direction or define the bolt cross-section nodes or select the layer of elements where the pre-tension loads will be applied. The user only needs to enter the list of elements forming the complete bolt and the program will automatically find the bolt normal direction and choose the cross-section nodes and elements. The code will find the centroid of the bolt, determine the bolt axial direction by examining the value of the bolt principal moment of inertia around the centroid then select the bolt cross-section by finding the lists of nodes and elements passing through the centroid and perpendicular to the axial direction. The details of the bolt modeling for the two cases are discussed below: Case 1: A bolted flange connection undergoing large rotation. As shown in Figure 59-1, the model consists of two flanges belonging to two different components (pipe segments, pressure vessels, or any other equipment) that are fastened together using 18 bolts. The finite element models for the bolts use a variety of low-order and higher-order solid elements including CHEXA, CTETRA, CPENTA and CPYRAM elements. A pre-tension force is first applied at the bolts and locked to ensure proper tightening. The assembly is then subjected to a rigid body rotation of 90 degrees. The purpose of this test case is to demonstrate BOLT1 usage for bolts modeled with solid elements as well as the capability of dealing with large rotation. Figure 59-1

As shown in Figure 59-2, the model consists of a solid block and a plate that are fastened together using 3 bolts.
